{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620833"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:46:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:46:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16647"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16647"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.04,0,0.3,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113106"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9338"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16647"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95138"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1003"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5007"},{"type":"tags","id":"5020"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22116"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113106"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman taking warfarin for atrial fibrillation presents to the Emergency Department with epistaxis. Her International Normalised Ratio (INR) is 8.2 (2.0-3.0).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe requires urgent reversal of anticoagulation for a surgical procedure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of warfarin that needs to be reversed?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prevention of the gamma-carboxylation of clotting factors II, VII, IX and X","Vitamin-K mediated direct inhibition of activated factor X","Inhibition of platelet cyclooxygenase","Activation of vitamin K inhibition of clotting factors II, VII, IX and X","Enhancement of fibrinolysis by inhibiting vitamin K"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWarfarin works as an anticoagulant by inhibiting vitamin K epoxide reductase. By doing this, it \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevents\u003C/strong\u003E the vitamin K-dependent process of \u003Cstrong\u003Egamma carboxylation of factors II, VII, IX and X. \u003C/strong\u003EWithout gamma carboxylation, these factors are not activated and therefore do not function in the clotting cascade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin-K mediated direct inhibition of activated factor X\u003C/strong\u003E - Factor X inhibition is not mediated by vitamin K; direct factor Xa inhibitors like rivaroxaban work through this mechanism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of platelet cyclooxygenase\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of aspirin, not warfarin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of vitamin K inhibition of clotting factors II, VII, IX and X\u003C/strong\u003E - Vitamin K activates rather than inhibits these clotting factors\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhancement of fibrinolysis by inhibiting vitamin K\u003C/strong\u003E - Warfarin does not affect the fibrinolytic system\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment options for warfarin reversal include vitamin K administration and fresh frozen plasma which contains the vitamin K-dependent clotting factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin K is essential for the gamma-carboxylation of clotting factors II, VII, IX, and X in the liver.","Warfarin works by inhibiting vitamin K epoxide reductase, preventing the recycling of vitamin K and therefore limiting the activation of vitamin K-dependent clotting factors","Beriplex and FFP contain vitamin K-dependent clotting factors and can be used to reverse warfarin anticoagulation."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Robinson D, McFadyen J, Merriman E, Wee TC, Baker R, Tran H. Updated recommendations for warfarin reversal in the setting of four-factor prothrombin complex concentrate. Medical Journal of Australia. https://doi.org/10.5694/mja2.52538"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95138"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16647"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95138"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-09T18:16:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-09T18:16:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9338"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113106"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior